node.text: Swimming for something BIGGER! A 2018 study revealed only 13% of our oceans are considered truly wild, but what's worse is this (scary) statistic has gone relatively unnoticed. Why? Well, partly because the sea (and its inhabitants) require a bigger "voice" to be heard. To quote the great Sir @davidattenborough “This is a communication challenge rather than a scientific one. We need to make it easy for the world to understand the issues and to enable an increasingly urban population to connect with nature and feel a shared responsibility for it.” Which is exactly why last weekend myself and the Talisker team took to the water (equipped with a plentiful supply of bananas) in support of @Talisker and @Parley.TV on their mission to Rewild Our Seas and created this short film (see link in my bio for more information) #TaliskerParley #RewildOurSeas #WildSpirit

node.text: Continuing to share my strategies for coping with isolation based on the teachings of my new book #TheArtOfResilience documenting the 157 days I spent at sea (share and tag someone who needs to hear this) Research published in the Frontiers in Human Neuroscience took a group of athletes and had them cycle to exhaustion. One group were shown subliminal visual cues of happy faces, the other group was shown subliminal visual cues of sad faces. What did they find? That “individuals cycled significantly longer when subliminally primed with happy faces”. They added, “These experiments are the first to show that subliminal visual cues relating to affect and action can alter perception of effort and endurance performance.” BIG thank you (again) to @BritishGQ for asking me to speak at this year’s GQ Heroes last year & @hendogq for being a brilliant interviewer 😃

node.text: Talking about the teachings of my new book #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for your copy) I never imagined the lessons learnt from 157 days at sea (staring at the ocean bed for over 1,000 hours left alone with my own thoughts) would become so relevant to helping so many people cope with isolation, adversity and a fear of the unknown. But if you (or anyone you know) can take comfort from the stoic teachings that I used at sea, then I will produce weekly videos on ancient stoic philosophy and strategies to cope with adversity that have been tried and tested over thousands of years. The topic of this first video is to briefly explain the origins of Stoicism and how it can help you identify the: Controllables vs Uncontrollables in your daily life. To quote Epictetus, "The chief task in life is simply this: to identify and separate matters so that I can say clearly to myself which are externals not under my control, and which have to do with the choices I actually control. Where then do I look for good and evil? Not to uncontrollable externals, but within myself to the choices that are my own."

node.text: This year's @talisker Whisky Atlantic Challenge has 103 rowers in 35 teams from 12 countries competing across 3,000 miles of ocean from (La Gomera) Tenerife to Antigua. As per the teachings of #TheArtOfResilience (SEE LINK IN BIO TO PRE ORDER) this isn't because I'm trying to achieve ketosis, but instead because research shows we can’t eat enough carbohydrates and store enough muscle glycogen to fuel ULTRA LONG endurance events. This is why research conducted at Harvard Medical School said, “While the maximum size of the glycogen reservoir available to an endurance runner depends on the size of the relevant muscles, it is possible to estimate the amount of accessible glycogen: A lean, male runner, for example, may be 45% skeletal muscle by mass, with half of that mass in his leg muscles; at 70 kg such an athlete would typically store 310 g of carbohydrate as muscle glycogen, and could store at most approximately 570 g, corresponding to approximately 1250 and 2270 kcal of leg muscle glycogen, respectively.” The study adds, “Considering the total carbohydrate-based energy reserve from muscle glycogen, liver glycogen, and plasma glucose, it becomes clear that normal carbohydrate stores alone would be insufficient to fuel a marathon.” The solution? Add fat. This is because research published in the American Journal of Physiology found working muscles consume a mixture of metabolic substrates, and the relative contributions of fat and carbohydrate to this mixture dynamically depend on exercise intensity and the size of available glycogen reservoirs. Siberian Reindeer Herding 🥜 … if you know, you know, haha 😂 Extract from my NEW book #BLUEPRINT (see link in bio for your copy) “As I watched on (and more questionable bottles of what I think was vodka were served) I continued to be amazed by the Evenki’s ability to find happiness in one of the world’s most hostile environments. Kissing girlfriends and wives… and dancing with legs that had covered over 180 miles in 3-ft snow, they truly understood How to Adventureand as a result had a profound and innate understanding of eustress and the long-lost concept of Eudaimonia. 

A term that originated in ancient Greece, it was a word emphasised by renowned philosophers Plato and Aristotle and for me (and many) it was a better word for “happiness.” This is because today we’re told the overriding rationale for our hobbies, work, relationships and the conduct of our daily lives is the pursuit of happiness. But ancient Greek philosophers believed this was too simple and the very term had many shortcomings. This is because by relying too heavily on the word “happiness” we are frequently (and wrongly) programed to avoid discomfort, fatigue, fear and testing situations.

This is why Eudaimonia is better. 

Roughly translated as “fulfilment”, it’s different from happiness since it openly accepts pain and struggling should form part of the process. Basically, it’s entirely possible to be fulfilled, but at the same time feel stressed and overburdened. This is a small (yet significant) psychological nuance that the word happiness doesn’t address, since it’s difficult to speak of being happy yet unhappy (or happy yet struggling) but it’s why I believe we adventure” 🔱

Why I wrote the #BLUEPRINT (see link in bio) 🔱 Taken directly from the final chapter; “Now, looking ahead to 2021, I had no idea what adventures awaited me since travel was still uncertain in the midst of a global pandemic, but that’s okay. That’s also the very nature of being an explorer as the mountains, oceans and jungles are entirely unpredictable and the weather, waves and seasons completely untameable. But the beauty of this book is that for me (and anyone reading it) it provides proven sports science principles (arranged in a systematic way) to prepare you for any expedition. Written to become a blueprint for anyone wanting to know How to Adventure, it’s my hope this book:

·  Becomes an essential item for any explorer’s backpack or bookcase.
·  Ushers in a new era of athletic adventures.
·  Brings the science and psychology of Adventure into the twenty-first century.

But most importantly, I hope the stories found throughout these pages have made you smile, the workouts have enriched your training and the teachings have inspired you to find a map, form a plan and embark on some incredible (truly Eudaimonic) adventures of your own” 🔱

node.text: Picking my favourite part of my NEW book #BLUEPRINT (see link in bio for your copy) is almost IMPOSSIBLE! But documenting the methodology of my WINTER (BASE) MESOCYCLE with the MASSIVE man hero @eddiehallwsm is 100% a HUGE highlight! To directly quote the book, “The focus is to create an ‘athletic base’ with a high volume of training at a low intensity while also improving work capacity (the body’s ability to perform and positively tolerate training of a given intensity or duration). This is achieved through a system of training called General Physical Preparedness (targeted at strength and endurance) that was pioneered in the old Soviet Union (1922 to 1991), but is done under conditions that take inspiration from the Spartan warrior society of ancient Greece (431-404 B.C) to build mental resilience as well as work capacity” 💪🏽 Tag friends, training partners and anyone who needs this book on their life 🙏
